SUMMARY:Patterns in Time
DESCRIPTION:A piece of music can be considered a pattern in time… the strange thing is that it doesn’t really exist until it is being played… A great work also captures something of the era in which it was written and then travels through time via aural tradition… or in notated form to be performed hundreds of years later. \nPatterns in Time\, a range of music from the 16th century to the present\, takes the audience through a journey not only through time but also through geographies and cultures from all over the world. \nThe concert begins with Spanish music inspired by the Andalusian flamenco tradition and will proceed to Renaissance and Baroque standards by Dowland\, Scarlatti and Bach. This will be followed by an extended and programmatic avant garde composition by the guitar virtuoso Pavel Steidl. \nThe second half of the recital will set off with some refreshingly tropical South American music and some tunes by Indian composers. This will be followed by music inspired by Turkey and end with Shamal\, an improvisatory piece consisting of extended techniques and percussion featuring a blend of sonorities and rhythms from the Middle East and the Indian subcontinent. \n \nSupported by: \n \n
